es and international societies to the emergence of natural history as an organized discipline. Along the way he describes the role of scientific ideas, popular fashion, religious motivations, literary influences, the increase of leisure time and disposable income, and the tendency of like-minded persons to form clubs. His comprehensive and entertaining discussion creates a vibrant portrait of a scientific movement inextricably woven into a particular culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aNATURE / General.2bisacsh  aAberdeen University.  aAlbert, Prince Consort.  aAnnals of Natural History.  aAurelian Society.  aBabington family.  aBarclay family.  aBedfordshire Society.  aBoerhaave, Herman.  aBolton, James.  aBritish Field Club.  aBrowne, Sir Thomas.  aBuxton family.  aChapone, Hester.  aClealand, James.  aCollingwood, Cuthbert.  aCrowther, James.  aDavy, Sir Humphrey.  aDohrn, Anton.  aEdinburgh Review.  aEntomological Club.  aFair Isle bird observatory.  aForster, Edward.  aGatty, Margaret.  aHoare family.  aHuxley family.  aInsect Immigration Committee.  aJameson, Robert.  aJournal of Ecology.  aKew Observatory.  aKnowlton, Thomas.  aLey, Augustin.  aLoddiges, Messrs (nurserymen).  aMacaulay family.  aMagazine of Natural History.  aNature Conservancy.  aPalaeontographical Society.  aQuarterly Review.  aRand, Isaac.  aRoyal Institution.  aRoyal Irish Academy.  aamenity movement.  aarchaeology.  abiology.  aconservation.  aecology.  aeducation.  aentomology.  afield-work.  ageology.  anatural history.  aornithology.  apatronage.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400843442zCo-access DOI >> clic